  <static seed="1334" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/SolveLinearEquations/SolveLinearEquationParentheses120.pg">
    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {54}={4-10\mathopen{}\left(C-6\right)}  }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="31" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\{1\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>Two alternative approaches are shown.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
 54       \amp = 4 -10(C-6)
          \amp  54       \amp = 4 -10(C-6) \\
 54       \amp = 4 +(-10) \cdot (C+(-6))
          \amp  54\mathbf{{}-4} \amp = 4 -10(C-6)\mathbf{{}-4} \\
 54       \amp = 4 +(-10) \cdot C+(-10) \cdot (-6)
          \amp  50 \amp = -10(C-6) \\
 54       \amp = 4 -10C +60
          \amp  \frac{50}{-10} \amp = \frac{-10(C-6)}{-10} \\
 54       \amp =      -10C +(4+60)
          \amp  -5 \amp = C-6 \\
 54       \amp =       -10C +64
          \amp  -5\mathbf{{}+6} \amp = C-6\mathbf{{}+6} \\
 54\mathbf{{}-64}       \amp =       -10C +64\mathbf{{}-64}
          \amp  1 \amp = C \\
 -10   \amp =   -10C
          \amp  C \amp = 1 \\
 \frac{-10}{-10}  \amp =    \frac{-10C}{-10} \\
 1     \amp =      C\\
 C     \amp =      1
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The solution to this equation is <m>1</m>. To stress that this is a value assigned to <m>C</m>, some report <m>C = 1</m>. We can also say that the solution set is <m>\{1\}</m>, or that <m>C\in\left\{1\right\}</m>. If we substitute <m>1</m> in for <m>C</m> in the original equation <m>54=4-10\mathopen{}\left(C-6\right)</m>, the equation will be true. Please check this on your own; it is an important habit.</p>
</solution>
